node.text:
Still I rise... On June 19, 1865, US Brigadier General Gordon Granger and his troops landed at Galveston, Texas, confirming the news that the Civil War had ended and that enslaved African Americans were now free. #Juneteenth commemorates this important milestone. Although the ratification of the 13th Amendment in December 1865 ultimately abolished slavery, the struggle for equality continues today. Through the lens of our nation’s iconic places, the National Park Service has a responsibility to advance understanding of our nation’s unique and complex history. We invite you to watch “Twenty & Odd,” which builds on the innumerable contributions of African Americans to the foundation of the nation and explores the trauma, resilience, and beauty of the African American experience.

#FindYourPark #NationalParkService

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Park Service in Fort McHenry National Monument & Historic Shrine. May be an image of standing.

node.text:
“By the Dawn's Early Light..." 🇺🇸⁣
⁣
On September 14, 1814, Francis Scott Key penned a poem which was later set to music and in 1931 became America’s national anthem, “The Star-Spangled Banner.” The poem, originally titled “The Defence of Fort M'Henry,” was written after Key witnessed the Maryland fort being bombarded by the British during the War of 1812. Following a 25-hour bombardment, onlookers glimpsed the huge 30x42-foot American flag flying over the fort, signaling that Fort McHenry had held.⁣
⁣
In 1933, @fortmchenrynps became an area administered by the National Park Service. Today, visitors to the fort can explore exhibits, participate in programs, and tour restored barracks. ⁣
⁣
Image: Three park rangers raise the large 15-star garrison flag inside #FortMcHenry. ⁣
⁣
#baltimore #starspangledbanner #flag #maryland #nationalanthem #warof1812

node.text:
For eight weeks this summer, the Native American youth crew from Capacity Builders, Inc. worked on trails maintenance, routine painting, carpentry, and rock wall building at both Canyon de Chelly National Monument and Navajo National Monument.
⁣
During the first few days of orientation, the crew got to know each other, learn about the park’s rich history, and explore the resources at Canyon de Chelly National Monument. Interns working at the park site also had the chance to meet with crew members and offer advice and assistance.⁣ Rangers shared with the youth the importance of preserving and protecting these unique cultural and natural resources that are in their very own backyards.
⁣
Learn more about youth programs and opportunities to get involved by following @npsyouth! ⁣
⁣
Image: from top to bottom: Trail crew members and interns standing with Interpretive Park Rangers in front of the Canyon de Chelly National Monument Welcome Center sign along with Interpretive Rangers; Seeking cell phone signal while enjoying a beautiful view of sunset at Navajo National Monument. Capacity Builder's, Inc trail crew members enjoy a short walk to catch sunset and seek cell phone coverage at Navajo National Monument; Trail crew members with Capacity Builder's, Inc sit with Ranger Ravis Henry inside the traditional Navajo shade house structure near the Welcome Center of Canyon de Chelly National Monument. Trail crew members heard stories from Ranger Ravis Henry on the sacredness of Canyon de Chelly according to the Navajo People, along with the history of the Navajo People.⁣
⁣
#FindYourPark #NPSYouth #CanyonDeChelleyNationalMonument #NavajoNationalMonument #NationalParks

node.text:
When you grow up, people stop asking you what your favorite dinosaur is. 🦖🦕⁣
⁣
It’s like they don't even care.⁣
⁣
Not today. What’s your favorite dinosaur? ⁣
⁣
At Dinosaur National Monument, you can travel back millions of years to a time when dinosaurs once ruled the Earth. (You are now picturing the banner at the end of that dinosaur movie fluttering to the ground.) Located on the Colorado and Utah border, the park's wild landscapes, topography, geology, paleontology, and history make it a unique resource for both science and recreation. ⁣
⁣
Images: Don’t worry, they’re mostly armless. Close up of several small dinosaurs figures exiting the building. ⁣
⁣
#dinosaur #dino #Colorado #Utah #nationalparkservice

node.text:
Like your hand reaching into a Pringles can, the Cooper’s Hawk pursues its prize with precision and speed. ⁣🤏
⁣
Incoming! (It’s all about the form.) The Cooper's hawk (Accipiter cooperii) is a medium-sized hawk native to the North American continent. Other common names for the Cooper's hawk include: big blue darter, chicken hawk, flying cross, hen hawk, quail hawk, striker, and swift hawk. Many of the names applied refer to their ability to hunt large and evasive prey using extremely well-developed agility. ⁣
⁣
Joshua Tree is home to a variety of bird species that are sure to delight the traveling birder. At any time of year, you may see year-round resident bird species such as the greater roadrunner, phainopepla, mockingbird, verdin, cactus wren, rock wren, mourning dove, Le Conte’s thrasher, and Gambel’s quail. Along with the Cooper’s Hawk, other resident birds of prey include the red-tailed hawk, American kestrel, and prairie falcon.⁣
⁣
Image: A Cooper’s hawk soars downward in a compact formation. NPS/Renata Harrison⁣ @joshuatreenps 
⁣
#birding #joshuatree #coopershawk #hawk #diving #california

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Park Service in Flight 93 National Memorial. May be an image of African daisy and nature.

node.text:
A common field one day.  A field of honor forever.⁣
⁣
On Tuesday morning, September 11, 2001, the U.S. came under attack when four commercial airliners were hijacked and used to strike targets on the ground. Nearly 3,000 people tragically lost their lives. Because of the actions of the 40 passengers and crew aboard one of the planes, Flight 93, further attacks were thwarted.⁣
⁣
Learn more about Flight 93 National Memorial at https://www.nps.gov/flni⁣
⁣
Image: The 93-ft tall Tower of Voices, pictured against a blue sky surrounded by yellow flowers, serves as both a visual and audible reminder of the heroism of the forty passengers and crew of United Flight 93. NPS/C. Claycomb⁣ @flight93_nps 
⁣
#pennsylvania #neverforget #september11 #nationalparkservice

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Park Service in Yellowstone National Park. May be an image of monument, outdoors and text that says 'FOR ENJOY ENJOYMENT He BENEFIT AND OF THE PEOPLE YELLOWSTON'.

node.text:
“What have they got in there, King Kong?” — Dr. Ian Malcolm⁣
⁣
Something like that. Yellowstone’s abundant and diverse wildlife are as famous as its geysers. There are nearly 300 species of birds, 16 species of fish, five species of amphibians, six species of reptiles, and 67 species of mammals, including Bison, the largest land mammal in North America. If we’ve said it once, we’ll keep saying it...wild animals are unpredictable and dangerous. Every year people are injured when they approach animals too closely.⁣
⁣
Hold onto your brochures! The following tips will keep you and park animals safe:⁣
⁣
🦬So your friends were so preoccupied with whether or not they could, they didn’t stop to think if they should? Never approach or pursue an animal to take its picture: use binoculars or telephoto lenses.⁣
⁣
🦬If you cause an animal to move, you're too close. It's illegal to willfully remain near or approach wildlife, including birds, within any distance that disturbs or displaces the animal.⁣
⁣
🦬Park in roadside pullouts when watching/photographing animals: do not block traffic. If the cup of water sitting on your dash starts to ripple, it may not be the best time to get out. ⁣
⁣
🦬Mommy’s very angry. Stay in or next to your car when watching bears. If a bear approaches or touches your car, honk your horn and drive away to discourage this behavior. ⁣
⁣
Enjoy watching Yellowstone’s animals but STAY SAFE! ⁣
⁣
Image: Enter Yellowstone National Park from the north entrance and you’ll get a chance to see the iconic Roosevelt Arch. @yellowstonenps ⁣
⁣
#yellowstone #nationalparkservice #wildlife #nature #gate #travel

node.text:
“It does not do to leave a live dragon out of your calculations, if you live near him.” – J.R.R. Tolkien⁣
⁣
Just saying. Preparedness is key to a fun, safe trip. Use a trip planning guide to be prepared for your next adventure in a national park. Use the NPS Trip Planning Guide and Checklist to help plan your trip. The guide provides key safety considerations to help you avoid some of the most common mistakes people make when visiting national parks. Find the link in our bio.⁣
⁣
P.S. Just like the unicorns, locations of dragon are not in the brochure. ⁣
⁣
Image: Hikers on rounded rocks in the distance are silhouetted against a colorful sunset sky. Jumbo Rocks Campground at Joshua Tree National Park is a great place to explore the park's bouldered landscape.⁣
⁣
#sunset #joshuatree #california #greatoutdoors #adventure

node.text:
The Tortugas Harbor Lighthouse is back! Taken down piece by piece in October 2020 and shipped off to Robinson Iron in Alabama for conservation work, the iron-plated lighthouse had been exposed to the elements and the effects of salty ocean air since its construction in 1876. Over its lifetime, the iron had corroded leading to significant deterioration in many areas, particularly around its base.⁣
⁣
The project isn't completely done yet -- additional restoration efforts to the interior and windows will continue on-site. Although the lighthouse and associated bastion will remain closed for several more months, the iconic view of the lighthouse is returning for visitors to enjoy.⁣
⁣
Swipe for a work-in-progress shot and some iconic lighthouse views. ⁣
⁣
NPS Photo 1 by M. Collier: From on top of Fort Jefferson, the lighthouse is visible. The sky is blue with clouds, and the ocean is visible in the background. ⁣
⁣
NPS Photo 2 by Curtis Hall: A work-in-progress shot of the exterior of the lighthouse being put together. Scaffolding surrounds the site, and an employee stands nearby. ⁣
⁣
NPS Photo 3 by M. Collier: A sign on a fence reads "Area Closed." The lighthouse and some of Fort Jefferson are behind the fence. The exterior of the lighthouse is visible, as well as the scaffolding surrounding it.⁣
⁣
NPS Photo 4 by M. Collier: The lighthouse and some of the top parts of Fort Jefferson are silhouetted against the night sky and the Milky Way.⁣
⁣
#DryTortugasNationalPark #DryTortugas #FindYourPark #lighthouse #florida #fortjefferson

node.text:
Every national park has a labor history to tell. From the laborers who built the Cheseapeake & Ohio Canal and laid the tracks of the first transcontinental railroad, to the “mill girls” who made cloth in Lowell’s textile factories, to the striking employees of Chicago’s Pullman Company, to the founder of the country's first permanent agricultural union, you’ll find their stories here. Get to work digging into the labor movement’s past at nps.gov/labor
⁣
Image: View of Lock 75 of the C&O Canal. Adjacent to the lock is a two-story log lockhouse. ⁣
⁣
@chesapeakeandohiocanal @lowellnps #laborday #nationalparkservice #canal

node.text:
When people walk past the “Closed Area” sign…⁣
⁣
When out and about, reduce your risk of injury by staying on trail and avoiding shortcuts. Many outdoor accidents happen when people go off the designated trail or walkway and don’t follow signs or posted information. If something does impact your activity, like a trail being closed, you may be better off turning around than taking a new route.⁣
⁣
Image: Close-up of an elk with a “Really? Hope that works out for them” look. ⁣
⁣
#elk #really #mood #grandtetonnationalpark #nationalparkservice

node.text:
It’s #NationalWildlifeDay!⁣
⁣
National parks offer a unique experience for watching wildlife. But with that privilege comes responsibility. Visitors are responsible for their own safety and for the safety of the animals, too. Simply put, keep your distance—no touching, no feeding, no harassing. Wanna take a picture? Use your zoom and give them room! ⁣
⁣
See more tips to watch wildlife safely by clicking the link in our bio. ⁣
⁣
Image: Infographic with text reading "Wildlife Petting Chart. #KeepWildlifeWild. NPS.gov". Illustration is of a bison with sections of the body labeled "Nope. How fast are you? Vacation over. Think again. Ouch. Umm, no. Do you have insurance?" Text reads "National parks offer a unique experience for watching wildlife. Animals in parks are wild-visitors have the amazing opportunity to view animals as they live and interact with each other in their natural homes. But with that privilege comes responsibility. Visitors are responsible for their own safety and for the safety of the animals, too. Remember to keep your distance, and enjoy your experience watching wildlife. No touching, no feeding, no harassing."⁣
⁣
#RecreateResponsibly #KeepWildlifeWild #wildlife #pettingchart #nationalparkservice
